    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Kew</placeName>
                    <date>March 31/67.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>We have no hopes for our pretty little baby whose fits increase in number &amp; duration—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Happily it suffers little, the nerves of motion exclusively being affected. This suspense is very painful.</p>
<p>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Hooker<ref target="#foot.f2"/> is pretty well</p>
<p>I keep her in bed next door to the child.</p>
<p>Ever dear old Darwin | Yrs affec | J D Hooker</p>
<p>Percival Wright was here today on his way to the Seychelles to spend some months collecting—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Hooker reported that <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2364.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Reginald Hawthorn Hooker</ref> had been suffering from convulsions (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5461.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 26 [and 27] March 1867</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5469.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 29 [March 1867]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2353.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Frances Harriet Hooker</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5255.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Perceval Wright</ref> spent six months in the Seychelles Islands in 1867, and brought back a collection of plants and animals (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2063.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">DNB</hi></ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
